<subSubSection id="E2FF65012B48FFCAFF588B30FC99678F" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588B30FDA26088" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF588B30FE866024" bold="true" box="[199,345,793,818]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Description.</emphasis>
Amorphous tubular-digitate sponge, 100 × 70 × 
<quantity id="6D1D9B6F2B48FFCAFC1F8B33FC016027" box="[896,990,794,818]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="270.0">270 mm</quantity>
diameter, with large central osculum, 
<quantity id="6D1D9B6F2B48FFCAFA118B30FF1C6043" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
in diameter, on tubular structure (
<figureCitation id="32DE2A0F2B48FFCAFDA28B14FD1C6040" box="[573,707,829,854]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1690,1712]" captionTargetBox="[163,1412,185,1651]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[163,1412,185,1651]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 28. Ircinia lividus sp. nov. A &amp; B. In situ; C–F. Skeletal architecture (C, x5; D, x10, E, 40; F, x65)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651506/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 28A, B</figureCitation>
). Surface smooth but undulating with sand grains observed in the preserved specimen. No ectosomal armour visible. Texture soft and spongy, compressible, tears easily. Colour in life dark blue-black; in preservative brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588B80FDC86744" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF588B80FEF160D4" bold="true" box="[199,302,937,962]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="32DE2A0F2B48FFCAFEDD8B80FE4860D4" box="[322,407,937,962]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1690,1712]" captionTargetBox="[163,1412,185,1651]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[163,1412,185,1651]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 28. Ircinia lividus sp. nov. A &amp; B. In situ; C–F. Skeletal architecture (C, x5; D, x10, E, 40; F, x65)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651506/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
C–F). Choanosomal skeleton consists of primary fibres, and abundant fine collagenous filaments. Primary fibres fully cored with foreign material 
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFCAC8BE7FC8D60F3" box="[819,850,974,997]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">viz</emphasis>
. sand grains, and are fascicular. Fascicles complex, compact and tangled. Secondary fibres uncored and often fasciculate though some sand particles may also be found. Primary fibres, 260 (240–295) µm in diameter, secondary fibres 58 (36–87) µm in diameter. Interstitial filaments, 4 (3–5) µm in diameter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588C74FC99678F" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF588C74FD446760" bold="true" box="[199,667,1117,1142]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Substratum, depth range and ecology.</emphasis>
This species is restricted to sandy sediment. These sponges were found in sheltered areas of reefs at a depth range of 
<quantity id="6D1D9B6F2B48FFCAFD438CABFC9D678F" box="[732,834,1154,1178]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="m" value="19.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="18.0">
18– 
<specimenCount id="BCE3FD032B48FFCAFC9A8CABFC9D678F" box="[773,834,1154,1178]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="generic">20 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E2FF65012B48FFCAFF588C8CFADB67A8" box="[199,1284,1189,1214]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588C8CFADB67A8" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" box="[199,1284,1189,1214]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF588C8CFE9167A8" bold="true" box="[199,334,1189,1214]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for the blue-black colour of the species (
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFCEE8C8CFC6367A8" authorityName="Samaai &amp; Pillay &amp; Janson" authorityYear="2019" box="[881,956,1189,1214]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lividus">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFCEE8C8CFC6367A8" box="[881,956,1189,1214]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">lividus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meaning black and blue, L.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E2FF65012B48FFCAFF588CE0FDF4655C" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588CE0FDF4655C" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF588CE0FEE467F4" bold="true" box="[199,315,1225,1250]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFE218CE3FDD667F7" authorityName="Nardo" authorityYear="1833" box="[446,521,1226,1249]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFE218CE3FDD667F7" box="[446,521,1226,1249]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Ircinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is large; the plastic nature of the species, in terms of overall morphology, creates difficulties in separating species (
<bibRefCitation id="CE744B7B2B48FFCAFD948CC4FCC66610" author="Cook &amp; Bergquist" box="[523,793,1261,1286]" firstAuthor="Cook" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="1094 - 1096" refId="ref41384" refString="Bergquist, P. R. &amp; Cook, S. D. C. (2002) Family Aplysinellidae Bergquist, 1980. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; Van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.), Systema Porifera. A guide to the classification of sponges. Fol. 1. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, New York, Boston, Dordrecht, London and Moscow, pp. 1094 - 1096. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 112" type="book chapter" year="2002">Cook &amp; Bergquist 2002</bibRefCitation>
) and as a result, few descriptions of 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFB308CC7FB256613" authorityName="Nardo" authorityYear="1833" box="[1199,1274,1262,1285]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFB308CC7FB256613" box="[1199,1274,1262,1285]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Ircinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are definitive. 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFF088D3BFF3D663F" authorityName="Nardo" authorityYear="1833" box="[151,226,1298,1321]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF088D3BFF3D663F" box="[151,226,1298,1321]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Ircinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are readily distinguished by the presence of fine filaments in the mesohyl, the fasciculation of primary fibres, foreign coring of primary, and an unarmored cortex (
<bibRefCitation id="CE744B7B2B48FFCAFC028D1CFB6D6658" author="Cook &amp; Bergquist" box="[925,1202,1333,1358]" firstAuthor="Cook" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="545 - 563" refId="ref42535" refString="Cook, S. de C. &amp; Bergquist, P. R. (1999) New species of dictyoceratid sponges from New Zealand: Genus Ircinia (Porifera: Demospongiae: Dictyoceratida). New Zealand Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research, 33, 545 - 563. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00288330.1999.9516899" type="journal article" year="1999">Cook &amp; Bergquist 1999</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFB598D1FFA566658" baseAuthorityName="Row" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[1222,1417,1333,1358]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arbuscula">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFB598D1FFA566658" box="[1222,1417,1333,1358]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Ircinia arbuscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’s original description by 
<bibRefCitation id="CE744B7B2B48FFCAFE028D73FD7E6664" author="Lendenfeld, R. von" box="[413,673,1369,1394]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="113 - 127" refId="ref46638" refString="Lendenfeld, R. von (1889) Das System der Spongien. Biologisches Zentralblatt, 9 (4), 113 - 127." type="journal article" year="1889">von Lendenfeld (1889)</bibRefCitation>
and the subsequent description by 
<bibRefCitation id="CE744B7B2B48FFCAFBB18D70FA886664" author="Samaai &amp; Gibbons" box="[1070,1367,1369,1394]" firstAuthor="Samaai" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 96" refId="ref48897" refString="Samaai, T. &amp; Gibbons, M. J. (2005) Demospongiae taxonomy and biodiversity of the Benguela region on the west coast of South Africa. African Natural History, 1, 1 - 96." type="journal article" year="2005">Samaai &amp; Gibbons (2005)</bibRefCitation>
differ from 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFF4A8D57FEE66680" authority="Samaai &amp; Pillay &amp; Janson, 2019" authorityName="Samaai &amp; Pillay &amp; Janson" authorityYear="2019" box="[213,313,1405,1430]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lividus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF4A8D57FEE66680" box="[213,313,1405,1430]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">I. lividus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="83A257E32B48FFCAFEDF8D54FE446683" box="[320,411,1405,1430]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" rank="species">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFEDF8D54FE4B6680" bold="true" box="[320,404,1405,1430]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in having a massive, amorphous or thickly encrusting morphology, primary fibres 
<quantity id="6D1D9B6F2B48FFCAFAD78D54FF6266AC" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="75.0" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="50.0">50–100 µm</quantity>
wide, filaments 
<quantity id="6D1D9B6F2B48FFCAFEE78D8BFE1066AC" box="[376,463,1442,1466]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 µm</quantity>
wide, and a tough ectosome of foreign spicules. Three species of 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFB2A8D8BFADF66AF" authorityName="Nardo" authorityYear="1833" box="[1205,1280,1442,1465]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFB2A8D8BFADF66AF" box="[1205,1280,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Ircinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are described from the WIO. These are 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFE4C8DEFFCD366C8" authority="(Ridley, 1884)" authorityName="Ridley" authorityYear="1884" baseAuthorityName="Ridley" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[467,780,1477,1502]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="conulosa">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFE4C8DEFFD8A66C8" box="[467,597,1477,1502]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">I. conulosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CE744B7B2B48FFCAFDF58DECFCDB66C8" author="Ridley" box="[618,772,1477,1502]" firstAuthor="Ridley" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="366 - 482" refId="ref48144" refString="Ridley, S. O. (1884) Spongiida. In: Report on the Zoological Collections made in the Indo-Pacific Ocean during the Voyage of H. M. S. Alert 1881 - 2. British Museum (Natural History), London. Istituti Biologici della Universita di Genova, 58 - 59, 69 - 75, pp. 366 - 482 + 582 - 635." type="journal article" year="1884">Ridley, 1884</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFC828DEFFA9566C8" authority="(Vacelet, Vasseur &amp; Levi, 1976)" authorityName="Vacelet, Vasseur &amp; Levi" authorityYear="1976" baseAuthorityName="Vacelet, Vasseur &amp; Levi" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[797,1354,1477,1502]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cylindracea">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFC828DEFFC6066C8" box="[797,959,1477,1502]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">I. cylindracea</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CE744B7B2B48FFCAFC4C8DECFA9E66C8" author="Vacelet, Vasseur &amp; Levi" box="[979,1345,1477,1502]" firstAuthor="Vacelet" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref52106" refString="Vacelet, J., Vasseur, P. &amp; Levi, C. (1976) Spongiaires de la pente externe des recifs coralliens de Tulear (sud-Ouest de Madagascar). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris, A, Zoologie, 49, 1 - 116." type="journal article" year="1976">Vacelet, Vasseur &amp; Lévi, 1976</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFA138DEFFE786514" authority="(Hyatt, 1877)" authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1877" baseAuthorityName="Hyatt" baseAuthorityYear="1877" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="intertexta">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFA138DEFFEDC6517" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">I. intertexta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CE744B7B2B48FFCAFE8C8DC3FE406514" author="Hyatt" box="[275,415,1514,1538]" firstAuthor="Hyatt" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="481 - 554" refId="ref45134" refString="Hyatt, A. (1877) Revision of the North American Poriferae, with Remarks upon Foreign Species. Part II. Memoirs of the Boston Society of Natural History, 2, 481 - 554, pls. XV-XVII." type="journal article" year="1877">Hyatt, 1877</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFE2A8DC3FD8A6514" authority="Samaai &amp; Pillay &amp; Janson, 2019" authorityName="Samaai &amp; Pillay &amp; Janson" authorityYear="2019" box="[437,597,1513,1538]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lividus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFE2A8DC3FD8A6514" box="[437,597,1513,1538]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Ircinia lividus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFDC18DC0FD656514" bold="true" box="[606,698,1513,1538]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="83A257E32B48FFCAFDC18DC0FD656514" box="[606,698,1513,1538]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is readily distinguished from these 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B48FFCAFBC78DC3FB7C6517" authorityName="Nardo" authorityYear="1833" box="[1112,1187,1514,1537]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Ircinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFBC78DC3FB7C6517" box="[1112,1187,1514,1537]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Ircinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by its visibly short tubular form, large diameter of fibres, fasciculation of both primary and secondary fibres, and the prodigious coring of sand in the primary fibres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E2FF65012B48FFCAFF588E7CFCA66584" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="key">
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588E7CFDDC6578" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" box="[199,515,1621,1646]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B48FFCAFF588E7CFDDC6578" bold="true" box="[199,515,1621,1646]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Key diagnostic characters.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588E53FCA66584" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" box="[199,889,1657,1682]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">• Sponge tubular-digitate with dark blue-black colouration.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E2FF65012B48FFCAFF588EB7FBC565CC" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588EB7FD7365A0" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" box="[199,684,1693,1718]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">• Texture soft, spongy and compressible.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B48FFCAFF588EEBFBC565CC" blockId="63.[151,1437,613,1754]" box="[199,1050,1729,1754]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">• Primary fibres thin, filaments very thin and cored with foreign material.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
